# Tech principles — {{COMPANY_NAME}}

> The criteria we apply when making architectural decisions. ADRs
> filed via `/decision` should reference these — either honoring
> them or *consciously breaking* them with reasoning.
>
> Principles change rarely, and only via ADR (file an ADR that
> supersedes the old principle, then edit this file).

## Principles

### {{Boring tech first}}

{{Default to mature, widely-deployed tools (Postgres, Redis, Kafka,
Linux) over novel ones. Break this only when there's a measured
limit the boring choice hits AND evidence the novel one fixes it.
"Better DX" is not evidence. "Faster benchmark" is not evidence
unless the slower benchmark is actually a problem in production.}}

### {{Buy what's commodity, build what's differentiating}}

{{Auth, payments, email, error tracking, log aggregation — buy.
The thing that makes the company unique — build. The line shifts
over time; revisit at quarterly review.}}

### {{Simplicity beats cleverness}}

{{The clever solution that one person understands is worse than
the boring solution five people understand. Optimize for "next
engineer onboarding" cost, not "current engineer cleverness"
benefit.}}

### {{Contracts before clients}}

{{Define the contract (data model, endpoint shape, event schema)
before writing the code that consumes it. Contracts live in
`<orchestrator>/contracts/`. Drift between contract and
implementation is a bug.}}

### {{Honest reporting both directions}}

{{When a sub-kit reports green, it ran the gate and saw green.
When it reports stuck, the orchestrator believes it. Same for the
orchestrator's reports back to the user. No "looks fine" without
verification.}}

### {{Reversible by default}}

{{Prefer changes that can be undone in a deploy cycle (feature
flags, additive schema migrations, blue-green deploys) over those
that can't (destructive migrations, ABI breaks, vendor lock-in).
When you must make an irreversible change, write the ADR before
making it, not after.}}

### {{Add your own…}}

{{Each principle is one to three sentences. The more principles
you have, the less they constrain. Aim for 5–8 that actually shape
calls; more becomes wallpaper.}}

